CEOs, politicians, lead singers - these are busy people. But he and his research team felt maybe there was something else going on, an actual difference in the brain that they could measure. So, they did a study. They took a bunch of regular people - college kids mostly - and randomly made them either powerful or powerless. If you got picked for the powerless group, you were told to write a diary entry about a time you really depended on someone else - at work, at school, at home. If you were put in the powerful group, on the other hand, you were asked to write about a time when you were powerful, important, and you knew it. Like this one woman, Obhi, says, who wrote about meeting her sister's new boyfriend for the first time.
